<subSubSection id="17ABA5A2EA2C0C3EFF4DF8A2F5C45123" lastPageId="52" lastPageNumber="53" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="5F0EF629EA2C0C3EFF4DF8A2F5C45123" blockId="51.[151,1436,1907,2011]" lastBlockId="52.[151,1436,152,912]" lastPageId="52" lastPageNumber="53" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA2C0C39FF4DF8A2F034549A" bold="true" box="[198,326,1907,1933]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body yellowish to reddish brown, shining. Length of pronotum + elytra = 2.8–3.5 mm (males), 2.7–3.2 mm (females). Head densely punctate, punctures larger than those of pronotum. Pronotum widest at basal two-fifths; sides weakly, obtusely rounded at basal two-fifths; basal angles obtuse; broad, ratio length:width = 1:1.7; finely punctate with faint, reticulate microsculpture. Elytra wider than pronotum, ratio length:width = 1:0.75; with 9 regular, closely punctate striae; striae 6 and 7 do not reach apex, stria 8 does not reach base, stria 1 weakly impressed; intervals with scattered minute punctures, transversely striolate. Antennal club (
<figureCitation id="C78AEAACEA2B0C3EFEC7FEDDF0DD5231" box="[332,431,268,294]" captionStart="FIGURES 143–147" captionStartId="51.[151,271,1764,1788]" captionTargetBox="[258,1326,970,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-326@51.[254,1332,964,1740]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 143–147. Platyhydnobius arizonensis. 143. Right antenna, dorsal view. 144. Mandibles, dorsal view. 145. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 146. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 147. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 145, 147), 0.4 mm (Fig. 146), 0.5 mm (Figs. 143, 144)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310991/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Fig. 143</figureCitation>
) moderately broad, ratio club width:length = 1:2.9; width ratio of antennomeres 7:8:9 = 1.5:1:2.0. Mandibles (
<figureCitation id="C78AEAACEA2B0C3EFE37FEE3F351525B" box="[444,547,306,332]" captionStart="FIGURES 143–147" captionStartId="51.[151,271,1764,1788]" captionTargetBox="[258,1326,970,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-326@51.[254,1332,964,1740]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 143–147. Platyhydnobius arizonensis. 143. Right antenna, dorsal view. 144. Mandibles, dorsal view. 145. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 146. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 147. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 145, 147), 0.4 mm (Fig. 146), 0.5 mm (Figs. 143, 144)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310991/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Fig. 144</figureCitation>
) moderately elongate, a thin plate forming inner margin apically. In both sexes, all femora unarmed; all tibiae slender, spinose on outer margin, protibiae and mesotibiae weakly widened apically, male mesotibia weakly curved. 
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA2B0C3EFD56FEAEF251528E" bold="true" box="[733,803,383,409]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Male.</emphasis>
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="C78AEAACEA2B0C3EFC25FE51F560528D" box="[942,1042,384,410]" captionStart="FIGURES 143–147" captionStartId="51.[151,271,1764,1788]" captionTargetBox="[258,1326,970,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-326@51.[254,1332,964,1740]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 143–147. Platyhydnobius arizonensis. 143. Right antenna, dorsal view. 144. Mandibles, dorsal view. 145. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 146. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 147. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 145, 147), 0.4 mm (Fig. 146), 0.5 mm (Figs. 143, 144)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310991/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Fig. 145</figureCitation>
) with median lobe elongate, apex evenly narrowed. Parameres longer than median lobe, with small lobes laterally near base, flat, apices expanded, thin, with two setae dorsally before apex and many small setae covering apices. 
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA2B0C3EFB5DFE1CF44B52F0" bold="true" box="[1238,1337,461,487]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Female.</emphasis>
Coxites (
<figureCitation id="C78AEAACEA2B0C3EFF14FE25F0765119" box="[159,260,500,526]" captionStart="FIGURES 143–147" captionStartId="51.[151,271,1764,1788]" captionTargetBox="[258,1326,970,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-326@51.[254,1332,964,1740]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 143–147. Platyhydnobius arizonensis. 143. Right antenna, dorsal view. 144. Mandibles, dorsal view. 145. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 146. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 147. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 145, 147), 0.4 mm (Fig. 146), 0.5 mm (Figs. 143, 144)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310991/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Fig. 147</figureCitation>
) moderately elongate, cylindrical, with apical and subapical setae; styli elongate, inserted at apices of coxites. Sternite 8 (
<figureCitation id="C78AEAACEA2B0C3EFE12FDCBF08F5123" box="[409,509,538,564]" captionStart="FIGURES 143–147" captionStartId="51.[151,271,1764,1788]" captionTargetBox="[258,1326,970,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-326@51.[254,1332,964,1740]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 143–147. Platyhydnobius arizonensis. 143. Right antenna, dorsal view. 144. Mandibles, dorsal view. 145. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 146. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 147. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 145, 147), 0.4 mm (Fig. 146), 0.5 mm (Figs. 143, 144)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310991/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Fig. 146</figureCitation>
) rounded apically; anterior apophysis broad, apex rounded.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="17ABA5A2EA2B0C3EFF4DFD91F0A95087" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="5F0EF629EA2B0C3EFF4DFD91F31B51E1" blockId="52.[151,1436,152,912]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA2B0C3EFF4DFD91F015514D" bold="true" box="[198,359,576,602]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species occurs across forested northern North America and seemingly with at least one disjunct population in the south in the montane forests of Mount Graham, Arizona (
<figureCitation id="C78AEAACEA2B0C3EFBF7FDB9F5965195" box="[1148,1252,616,642]" captionStart="FIGURE 148" captionStartId="52.[151,255,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[232,1354,970,1837]" captionTargetId="figure-325@52.[232,1354,970,1837]" captionTargetPageId="52" captionText="FIGURE 148. Known North American localities of Platyhydnobius arizonensis (black dots) and P. validus (open squares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310994" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310994/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Fig. 148</figureCitation>
). We have seen specimens from 
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA2B0C3EFEE8FD5FF0A051BF" bold="true" box="[355,466,654,680]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<collectingCountry id="27A6B6B9EA2B0C3EFEE8FD5FF0BF51BF" box="[355,461,654,680]" name="Canada" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Canada</collectingCountry>
:
</emphasis>
the provinces of 
<collectingRegion id="9D7538CBEA2B0C3EFD27FD5FF27951BF" box="[684,779,654,680]" country="Canada" name="Alberta" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Alberta</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="9D7538CBEA2B0C3EFC93FD5FF28251BF" box="[792,1008,654,680]" country="Canada" name="British Columbia" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">British Columbia</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="9D7538CBEA2B0C3EFC75FD5FF50451BF" box="[1022,1142,654,680]" country="Canada" name="Manitoba" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Manitoba</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="9D7538CBEA2B0C3EFB0FFD5FF43F51BF" box="[1156,1357,654,680]" country="Canada" name="New Brunswick" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">New Brunswick</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="9D7538CBEA2B0C3EFAD0FD5FF19751D8" country="Canada" name="Nova Scotia" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Nova Scotia</collectingRegion>
, Newfoundland, 
<collectingRegion id="9D7538CBEA2B0C3EFE39FD64F36251D8" box="[434,528,693,719]" country="Canada" name="Ontario" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Ontario</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion id="9D7538CBEA2B0C3EFDDBFD64F3DD51D8" box="[592,687,693,719]" country="Canada" name="Quebec" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Quebec</collectingRegion>
; 
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA2B0C3EFD37FD64F27251D8" bold="true" box="[700,768,693,719]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<collectingCountry id="27A6B6B9EA2B0C3EFD37FD64F38951D8" box="[700,763,693,719]" name="United States of America" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">USA</collectingCountry>
:
</emphasis>
the states of 
<collectingRegion id="9D7538CBEA2B0C3EFC29FD64F28651D8" box="[930,1012,693,719]" country="United States of America" name="Alaska" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Alaska</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="9D7538CBEA2B0C3EFBBBFD64F5E151D8" box="[1072,1171,693,719]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Arizona</collectingRegion>
. The absence of other records in the United States is puzzling.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5F0EF629EA2B0C3EFF4DFCD3F59C5054" blockId="52.[151,1436,152,912]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA2B0C3EFF4DFCD3F088500B" bold="true" box="[198,506,770,796]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Field notes and habitats.</emphasis>
Adults have been collected in mixed deciduous and coniferous forest habitats, most frquently with flight interecept traps and a few by evening car netting and in litter sifting.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5F0EF629EA2B0C3EFF4DFC9EF0A95087" blockId="52.[151,1436,152,912]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="6DC52A3BEA2B0C3EFF4DFC9EF028507E" bold="true" box="[198,346,847,873]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Seasonality.</emphasis>
Adults have been collected in the months of June to October, with the greatest numbers in July (93) and August (133).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
